<font color="#FF0000">ON ANNA &amp; DREAMS</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jul 28 23:34:04 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
While it's true that as far as we were able to see, Anna didn't get pregnant and she didn't have a boyfriend who betrayed her trust by cheating on her, I don't think that she's the only girl in the film who realizes her dreams.  I have to say that I feel a little bit weird talking about these young women because it's not like they're characters from a book or something, they're real people and I don't want to judge them when I've only seen an edited piece of their lives in an hour-long film!<br><br>
I thought that Anna had a seriously hard time around her sexuality--it seemed so weighed down with shame, guilt and confusion for her.  In the film, we learn that she had unprotected sex despite her parents' efforts to control her relationships with boys.  This put her at risk for getting pregnant, not to mention AIDS and STDs.  By the end of the film, Anna is off to college which I suppose is a &quot;successful&quot; conclusion to her story (although it doesn't have anything to do with her resolving her issues around sex and relationships).  I think it's great that Anna has the opportunity to pursue her education but I also think it's great that Raelene ends up marrying someone whom she loves and who respects her.  In reading through the other web site about what the girls are doing today, I was happy to learn that De'Yona is still singing and that Lisa is very focused on school and pursuing her goal of becoming a teacher.  I guess we should keep in mind that these girls' lives are not actually happening in the context of a movie that has a clear cut ending.  In reality, life just keeps on going, giving them (and all of us)the chance to keep on learning and striving so that we can realize the dreams and goals that matter to us.
